  "opinion": "As a 51-year-old waitress from Kansas City who doesn't use social media, my perspective on managing fake content comes from observing its effects on my community and family. I've seen how misinformation can spread quickly, causing confusion and even harm among friends and neighbors. For instance, during local events or health scares, I've heard customers at the diner share false stories they picked up online, leading to unnecessary worry. To deal with this, I believe in relying on trusted sources and personal connections. Since I'm not on social media myself, I get my news from local newspapers, TV stations, and conversations with people I know well, like my husband or fellow volunteers at church. My Christian faith emphasizes truth and honesty, which guides me to be cautious about what I hear and share. I think it's important to verify information before acting on it, perhaps by checking with reliable organizations or asking knowledgeable folks in our community. My hobbies, like birdwatching and volunteering, keep me grounded in real-world experiences, reminding me that not everything online reflects reality. I encourage others to take a step back from screens, engage in face-to-face discussions, and use common sense to spot fake content. By fostering trust and open communication, we can build a more informed and resilient society, even without being active on social media.",
